<div class="dablink">For the footballer, see <a href="/wiki/David_Ogilby" title="David Ogilby">David Ogilby</a>.</div>
<p><b>David MacKenzie Ogilvy</b>, <a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">CBE</a> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1911-06-23"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="06-23"><a href="/wiki/June_23" title="June 23">June 23</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1911" title="1911">1911</a></span>–<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1999-07-21"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="07-21"><a href="/wiki/July_21" title="July 21">July 21</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1999" title="1999">1999</a></span>), was a notable advertising executive. He has often been called "The Father of Advertising." In 1962, <i><a href="/wiki/Time_(magazine)" title="Time (magazine)">Time</a></i> called him "the most sought-after wizard in today's advertising industry." <sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> He was known for a career of expanding the bounds of both creativity and morality.</p>
